---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="sixpack Architecture" description="Current sixpack architecture.">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">Architecture</p>
      <h1>Readable source data, binary hot state.</h1>
      <p>
        sixpack is currently a small local table database. It keeps canonical
        data in append-only `.6` row segments and treats generated indexes as
        rebuildable acceleration.
      </p>

      <h2>Storage flow</h2>
      <pre><code>validate change
append .6
update runtime .6b projection
recover metadata/cache from .6 when needed</code></pre>

      <h2>Runtime projection</h2>
      <p>
        The hot projection is map-backed in memory. This keeps normal reads and
        edits off full-table traversal paths.
      </p>
      <pre><code>rows_by_id        row id -> .6 row pointer
lookup_ids        lookup field + key -> row ids
row_lookup_keys   row id -> lookup keys currently attached to that row</code></pre>

      <h2>Edit path</h2>
      <p>
        A patch resolves the row, appends the replacement operation, removes
        only that row's old lookup keys, inserts the new lookup keys, and
        updates the row pointer. The compact `.6b` file can be materialized
        from the runtime map when the engine needs a durable cache boundary.
      </p>

      <h2>Current limits</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>`db.watch(...)` live subscriptions are planned.</li>
        <li>`.6x` full-text search is reserved but not implemented.</li>
        <li>Compaction and segment sealing are not implemented yet.</li>
        <li>SQLite remains much faster for large transactional update batches.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
